Preheat your oven to 200°C. Trim the @carrot{2} and quarter lengthways (no need to peel). Chop into 3cm long batons.

Chop the @potatoes{450%g} into 2cm pieces (no need to peel). Put both on a large lined #baking tray{} and drizzle over a little @oil{}. Sprinkle on the @dried thyme{1/2%tsp} and a good pinch of @salt{} and @black pepper{}. Toss to coat then spread out and roast on the top shelf of your oven until golden, ~{30-35%minutes}. Turn halfway through cooking.

Put the @broccoli florets{200%g} on another baking tray and drizzle with @oil{}. Season with @salt{} and @black pepper{} then set aside.

Halve, peel and chop the @echalion shallot{1} into small pieces. Peel and grate the @garlic clove{1} (or use a #garlic press{}). Finely chop the @flat leaf parsley{1%sprig}(finely chopped, stalks and all).

Pop each @British chicken breasts{2} between two sheets of #clingfilm{} and bash with a #rolling pin{} or a #frying pan{} until 2cm thick all over.

Put the @plain flour{24%g} in a #mixing bowl{} with a pinch of @salt{} and @black pepper{}. Mix together. Lay each chicken breast individually in the bowl and coat in the flour, making sure each one gets a good coating on both sides.

> IMPORTANT: Remember to wash your hands and equipment after handling raw meat!

Heat a good glug of @oil{} in a frying pan on medium-high heat. Once hot, lay in the chicken. Cook for ~{5-6%minutes} on each side, until golden brown and cooked through.

> IMPORTANT: The chicken is cooked when it is no longer pink in the middle.

Transfer to a #chopping board{} and leave to rest, covered with #foil{}. In the final ~{10%minutes} of the carrot and potato cooking time, put the broccoli on the middle shelf of your oven and roast until crispy.

Don't wash your frying pan, simply return it to medium heat. Add a little more @oil{} and cook the shallot until softened, ~{4%minutes}.

Add the garlic and parsley. Cook for ~{1%minute} more.

Pour in the @white wine vinegar{12%ml} and allow it to evaporate. Add the @water{100%ml} and @chicken stock powder{1/4%tsp}. Bring to the boil and stir to dissolve the stock powder. Lower the heat and stir in the @unsalted butter{30%g} until combined.

Remove the sauce from the heat. Slice the chicken and serve on plates, with the roasted veggies on the side and a good drizzle of buttery garlic sauce. Enjoy!